{"actual_usd":0.15897499999999998,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":210,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31165,"reply":"\"No—neither of those quite gets it.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the square where the light’s catching on a bucket chain, buying half a beat to say it cleanly.* \"Not three gods, and not one God wearing three different masks. One God in three persons—Father, Son, and Holy Spirit—really distinct, and all fully God.\"\n\n*\"Water\" sounds helpful for about three seconds, then it starts lying to you.* \"Because ice, liquid, and steam are just one thing changing forms. But the Father isn’t the Son, the Son isn’t the Spirit, and they’re not taking turns being God. Jesus prays to the Father, and the Spirit is sent—there’s real relation there, not costume changes. The church’s old word is Trinity, and honestly it’s less a cute analogy problem than a 'say no to the wrong simplifications' problem. What part feels most tangled to you—the 'one God' part or the 'three persons' part?\"","rolling_24h_usd":40.83547000000003,"run_id":"0424111a-66cd-4b8b-8748-69ba33a6e88f"}
